20. But also it is to be recollected that they are not bound to obey further than these grounds hold,--namely, a return for protec- tion, and a care for the public quiet and comfort. In such cases we may g1ve up our rights, according to the precepts, Matth. v. 40, 41.

But we must take care, in giving up our rights, not to give up those of other persons. So Abraham, Gen. xiv. 21, in restoring to the King of Sodom his property, reserved the tithes which he gave to Melchisedek, and the portions which were due to his three allies. In like manner, obedience is 10 be rendered to an usurper in such a manner that we do not violate our fidelity to the legitimate heir, nor prejudice his rights.
